While deputies and human rights defenders argue about the consequences that the law would bring on the mandatory examination, scammers have already appeared in the country who trade with "false" certificates.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
They are mostly citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
A law has been in force since 1 December, according to which every working immigrant must take an exam to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule is applicable only to those who intend to work in the service provision sector, community service institutions, domestic services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised by the Federal Immigration Service, the exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the language test, but also the Russian history and the fundamentals of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even in order to receive and renew the work permit.
Citizens of countries where Russian is the official language are exceptions.
Persons who managed to obtain their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Utility, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, the Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 centers of this type are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and by the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law went into effect, often managed to ask the press this question: And what will this actually do?
What changes will the obligatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
First of all, answer the representatives of the Immigration Service, this will make it possible to reduce the number of people suffering from "labor slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of labor migrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Federal Immigration Service of Russia in Tajikistan.
The defence of their rights must be initiated before their departure.
Only an organized selection system will be able to solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are faced by immigrants without a profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the would-be immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the pretext of helping, put him on a "paid trip" to a creepy, narrow covacha, where he and dozens of others like him languish for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive countless complaints from our immigrants.
"In their homeland they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised wages," confirms the Head of the Labour Immigration Directorate of the Tajik Immigration Service, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't be angry, little boss!
In the meantime, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that not only do they not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as their own misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families even have nothing to feed the children, let alone dress them, put them on shoes and buy them for school.
When they reach adolescence, these boys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if you do not know the language, they recognize.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
However, when it comes to language law, rights advocates make an important point.
The tests will be conducted only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbidden to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause lies in bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money - from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only one thousand five hundred rubles.
Russian police employees know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and cases of extortion appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two hundred rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting"
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several "fake" certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The forged documents had been printed on standard color printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that "diplomas" cannot be bought, government officials and rights defenders converge.
So far, the authorities can promise migrant workers who would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
