Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
That certainly not, but, I repeat, I do not like to make this kind of comparison.
It needs to be said that even those countries we take as a model have to face a large number of problems.
If this were not the case, it would not be in their interest to collaborate with our office, don't you think?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public procurement mean for your Office? Does its impact manifest itself in any way?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet manifested itself in the control proceedings.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there is a certain need for a certain delay.
For now, it can be seen in the process of preparing future controls: we have initiated a new tool for "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, since the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process and similar are rectified.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or, rather, that it represents a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I believe that this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope that it will be so.
The problem that may arise is that the regulations "tighten" and that it is impossible to comply with them.
Already under the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the field of public procurement meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to toughen the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to attack it or take advantage of it and not punish those who commit a formal failure, which has no bearing on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this path taken us.
The prime minister has recently stated that the ODS would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called švarc system, with reference to being autonomous only on paper. What does this mean?
Is the "švarc" system banned or permitted?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such controls and demand obligations.
You can say, "We changed the law and we allowed it," but you can't say we'll do business as usual.
In the law on public procurement, the regulations are quite strict as to how formal action should be taken. And that's how it needs to be to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded because he does not meet the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This, in my opinion, is what we lack.
