The factual ban on the use of the term "butter spread" or the withdrawal of the classic light bulb from shops has been criticised.
A quality banana should have a length of 14 centimeters.
The Union apparatus often takes such decisions under pressure from one or another commercial or industrial lobby, whose demands in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (the Czech Republic, even with the threat of veto, vindicates the demands of its banks).
The interests of a lobby were behind the request, for example, that the highest quality bananas in the EU should be at least 14 centimeters long and could not present "abnormal curvatures".
