The Czechs, after six years of disputes with Germans and Austrians, successfully defended the designation of origin of Olomouc cottage cheese, but had to change the name of the national rum, whose tradition in our country dates back to the nineteenth century, and was renamed "tuzemák".
Only products made from sugar cane distillate can be called rum, but not those made from sugar beet.
In the official list of protected designations of origin of the EU, along with feta and gorgonzola cheeses known throughout the world, marzipan from the German city Lübeck or ham from Parma, there are already for example the biscuits of Karlovy Vary, the carp of Pohořelice and Třeboň and even the hop variety of Žatec.
As protected EU maras, they can be proud of the gingerbread of Pardubice and the wafers of Hořice v Podkrkonoší.
