It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, they reportedly pocketed 1.8 billion yuan in royalties.
In other words, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg demonstrates.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting a Chinese impersonator in court.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the impersonator has managed to secure Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
"We ourselves have caused this situation because surnames are not protected in Germany," says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
