The group has long since abandoned this commercial area, but managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be very careful," Wentzler says.
Both he and lawyer Pattloch advise German companies to be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international legislation on trademark rights, but what must be done is "to also register in China everything that may be eligible for protection", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the theme can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party licensing fees by name, as Wentzler explains.
