Indeed, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members in a 15-hour evening meeting, are truly worrying.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also says that jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
However, what does that "principles" mean?
This was and remains open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists will take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal leeway that goes with it, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what a new article suggests: in all matters relating to sharia it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power in all of Sunni Islam.
It doesn't have to be this way, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that - in fact - would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During the Mubarak dictatorship these courts served to exert harsh repression on the opposition.
After the fall of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As the draft states, the state must protect "the true essence of the Egyptian family" and "promote its morals and values."
It is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
To put it bluntly, it is nothing more than censorship.
By the way, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
On the other hand, another forbids offending or slandering Prophet Mohammed and his legacies.
However, it is not clear what an offence is and how it is to be punished.
Equally dubious is the formulation prohibiting "offending persons."
Is a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
A matter of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been presented to Morsi for his signature and that, according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to Egyptians to be submitted to a referendum.
"The revolution is back"
For weeks, the opposition has been closing ranks in the face of the Islamists' superiority.
Ten thousand people gathered in unusual harmony on Friday afternoon in Tahrir del Caryo's Square and vowed to derail the Act before it can take effect.
"The revolution has returned and we will end up winning," says Hamdin Sabbahi, who is third on the presidential election lists.
Nobel Peace Prize laureate and former head of the International Atomic Energy Agency, Mohamed ElBaradei, said the draft constitution should be "in the dustbin of history."
On Twitter, he accused Morsi's supporters of wanting to lead a "coup against democracy."
"When he calls the referendum we will go to his palace and overthrow him," said opposition leader Jasser Said.
"We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers has not yet been atoned for," opposition politician Chaled Ali was quoted in Egyptian media.
And several judges announced that they did not wish to supervise the referendum, so it would not be considered valid.
"The Koran is our constitution"
For its part, the well-organized Muslim community called for a counter-demonstration; just in case not in Tahrir Square, but after a prayer on the other side of the Nile, in front of Cairo University.
Many veiled women and supporters of the Salafists took part in it shouting: "the people demand the application of divine law."
They demanded Morsi "clean up the country," while proclaiming, "the Koran is our constitution."
A struggle for sovereignty over symbolic Tahrir Square, where it all began, would have led to a situation akin to a civil war.
Clearly, Morsi's supporters did not want to risk such a thing happening.
The Muslim Brotherhood claimed that both opponents of the draft constitution and supporters of it would have expressed their opinions loud and clear.
Now the time would have come to let the people decide at the ballot box which direction the country should take.
In this sense, it seems that the Islamists' draft is guaranteed a majority.
"The expression 'Human Rights' does not even appear"
Hafez Abu Saeda is furious with this forced constitutional process that should actually have lasted until February and included all social forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and president of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were held in prison or faced trial during the Mubarak dictatorship.
Not because he shared his ideology, but because for him human rights are indivisible.
For this reason he was beaten, convicted and imprisoned.
"And now the expression 'human rights' does not even appear in the new constitution," he lamented in a conversation with the newspaper "Welt am Sonntag".
The extension of Morsi's powers to the three branches of government made this lawyer resign himself.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
"Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it," Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could backfire.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: "You are conceiving a monster that you cannot control."
Norwegian rakfisk: the smelliest fish in the world?
Norway's five million people enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country's success has anything to do with its greed for smelly fish?
Take a series of excessively cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty and damp football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
You can then smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway's delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
It's snowy. The scenery is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how smelly you prefer it, up to a year.
As it gets dark and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival here in Fagernes dedicated to this most captivating, so to speak, delicacy.
"You eat raw and then drink a glass of aquavit in one gulp," says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the "General of the Rakfisk," who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking significant amounts of the drink in one gulp.
"Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk," says Havard.
The drink can kill the smell.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it near your nose, it's not bad; It's not unlike a portion of sushi that has traveled a few miles by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, when poverty plagued Norway and when, before refrigeration, fish was stored during the autumn immersed in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, migrating mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is increasing rapidly; More than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a comprehensive social services system.
A stream of inhabitants from Sweden, the old rival and until not too long ago much richer than Norway, come to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered something important, an essential, if rather smelly, part of Norway's past.
It is among the most expensive dishes that can be bought.
But in fact, everything is expensive. A beer rod or sandwich costs you a whopping €10 ($14) each.
Norway is not usually on the agenda of international news and most Norwegians like it that way.
Here people are still reluctant to utter the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who gunned down and murdered 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as "the July 22 event."
Norwegians find it hard to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own would be capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway's current wealth is the growth, since the early 70s, of one of the world's largest oil and gas industries.
"But oil is not the only reason we are doing so well," says Anna, our waitress, as she passes trays of rakfisk and, with her long blonde hair and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
"We are, as you say, prudent people."
His English, like that of most people in this country, is impeccable.
"We don't like to brag, we don't like ostentation."
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; All but a small percentage of the money from this industry is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn't have during the years leading up to the worldwide financial crisis, Norway kept its wallet tightly shut.
"As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we're happy," says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a burst of laughter.
I'm in the snow queuing up to eat something; I've had enough of Rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to savor.
But at night, that smelly fish returns.
The hotel I'm staying at is one of many places where a rakfisk dinner is held where diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that tests the nostrils the most.
A live television has connected with a presenter wearing a bow tie and surrounded by rakfisk dishes.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls off his chair, perhaps overcome by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the vapors of all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Peña Nieto faces a rough start
As Mexico's incoming president, Enrique Peña Nieto, prepares to take office, the BBC's Will Grant discusses the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad these days.
In a city that, in the best of circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads leading to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto, will receive the presidential sash and assume the management of the nation.
He faces a complicated task.
Mexico has been performing well economically during the outgoing government of Felipe Calderón, but the country is immersed in a war against drug trafficking that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My administration has a great commitment to the Mexican people to reduce violence," Mr. Peña Nieto explained earlier this week to U.S. President Barack Obama in the Oval Office.
"I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal."
Before rubbing shoulders with the U.S. president, Mr. Peña's previous political experience was as governor of his home state of Mexico.
A highly populous and fast-growing state surrounding the capital; Opinions about the new leader are divided in this territory in which he used to move.
A sincere man
In the bucolic city of Valle del Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Its residents credit it with the growth of tourism in the place and the construction of infrastructure.
To get to the city you can drive on one of Mr. Peña Nieto's new roads, which is a huge improvement compared to the cracked and potholed roads that were rehabilitated.
You can also see plaques with his name at the entrance of a modern sports center and an impressive interactive museum on climate change.
"We are confident that he will succeed in making real and lasting change," says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a deputy from Mr. Peña Nieto's party, the PRI.
"Particularly, when it comes to security and the economy, we look forward to the interesting and real change that our country so badly needs."
After an uninterrupted period of 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted by Vicente Fox in 2000.
Deputy Olvera admits that, after 12 years outside the presidential palace of Los Pinos, within the party there are many expectations regarding Enrique Peña Nieto.
It also rejects the opposition's description of the lack of essence of the new president.
"He is a very sincere man, very committed and with an excellent vision of the country.
He is a fantastic statesman and, above all, he is a person who knows how to listen."
On the other side of the state, however, that's not the impression many people have of their former governor.
In Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Neza, the contrast with the cobbled streets of Valle del Bravo could not be greater.
Hidden under elevated stretches of highway it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems of the municipality are also hard and urban.
Earlier this year, the military was called upon to intervene to help in the fight against drug gangs operating in the neighborhoods, and violence against women is particularly serious.
In a desert plot next to a garbage dump, the bodies of dozens of murdered women have been left abandoned in just the last two years.
More than 1,000 women were murdered in the state of Mexico while Mr. Peña Nieto was governor, a much higher rate than that of Ciudad Juárez, unfortunately notorious for its violence and a place that is synonymous with the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's critics say, at best, that he failed to address the problem of femicide while in office.
Critics accuse his administration of turning a blind eye.
In a concrete house, typical of the run-down neighborhood, Irinea Buendía has to struggle to hold back tears as she shows me photographs of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version of events, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes her partner murdered her.
"When I got to his house, it looked as if his body had been cleaned," Ms. Buendía recalls.
"There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared."
As her mother recounts the story, a photograph of Mariana watches from the walls, next to a cross on which a single word is read: Justice.
Yet that is exactly what the family says he has been denied.
"The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a whiner.
What they want is for you to just accept what they say and shut up."
"But that cannot be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence," he says.
The presidential sash that President Peña Nieto will receive on Saturday will come with enormous responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crime in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has vowed to prioritize them during his term.
"I hope he's the same kind of president he was when he was governor," says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
Yet that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning Failed to Report Wrongdoing, Prosecutors Say
Prosecutors try to deal with allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison
Trial focuses on Manning's stint at Quantico military prison in Virginia
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's imprisonment was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors sought to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the ill-treatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During the prosecution's questioning of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, U.S. Attorney Major Ashden Fein said records of weekly visits by unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no allegation about his treatment.
The questioning, which took place during a hearing following the defense's request to dismiss the case on the grounds that his imprisonment had been harsh and that it had already been sufficiently punished, came a day after Manning had testified that he had contemplated suicide while in detention.
The Army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
WikiLeaks later published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday's hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico military prison, where he was held in maximum confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers reportedly asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had described the treatment given to him by the guards as "excellent" and the treatment received at the facility in general as "very professional."
The forms do not show any allegations of mistreatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about her treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that visiting officers had discussed those issues and indicated that they would be addressed, but that they did not record those issues in the record.
"They wrote 'no incident' (after talking about the issues) but this doesn't necessarily mean I wouldn't have mentioned any issues," Manning said.
The judge, Army Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not reported the treatment she was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining suicide intentions she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during that meeting was to obtain the reduction of the "injury prevention" regime under which he found himself.
The military said he had been placed under the restrictive regime, which is one grade below that of possible suicide watch, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the general staff to know that I was OK and (wanted) to stop being under injury prevention ... to be able to enjoy what, from my point of view, is a better quality of life," Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to the military prison at the Marine Corps base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and once lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
"My world was just reduced to Camp Arafjon, to that cage," Manning said Thursday.
"I thought I was going to die in that cage."
Manning said that, once transferred to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning said he always had a light coming from outside pointed at his eyes as he slept.
He said that if the guards couldn't see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning's treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth military prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation he had made in Thursday's deposition that after he was forced to sleep naked one night in his cell in Quantico, he was forced during a morning count to stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners.
Manning had testified that she had never been given the opportunity to cover herself with the blanket during the count.
During the judge's questioning Friday, Manning said she deduced from the guard's order that she drop the blanket she could have covered herself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered her to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning said she had told the officer she could have used the elastic on her underwear or flip-flops to harm herself but had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers hope the judge will at least take into account his experiences during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence if he were convicted at the court-martial, which is due to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held under the rules applicable to any detainee in maximum custody at Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperation with the enemy, unlawfully provoking the posting of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
He claims many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities.
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; He says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times.
Navarrette says Mexican-Americans find themselves caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, he had barely walked down the esplanade and arrived at the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Signs indicated the way to two lines: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners."
I stood there for a few seconds not sure where I should go.
Growing up in Central California, I've been called "Mexican" all my life.
This is ethnic shorthand, just as my friends in Boston refer to themselves as "Irish" or my friends in New York call themselves "Italian."
Later I decided on "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather's homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply American.
I speak Spanish. Good enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don't have the vocabulary level of a native and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I took my U.S. passport and stood in line for foreigners.
I thought back to that moment this week when Mexican President-elect Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
On the agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, were: immigration, drugs and trade.
Peña Nieto was also eager to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why a Mexican is now as likely to stay in Mexico as he is to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trading bloc in North America.
In addition, Peña Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of rancor.
Most Americans probably never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them of it are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that involves the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how the Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And Montezuma's sons are put on a war footing.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that is really challenging is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
Are we talking about resentment?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, somewhere in our family tree, there was a person, maybe the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunity in Mexico and had to go north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor village, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Not Mexico.
And, although we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and having had good jobs, we can never lose sight of the fact that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican dream.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look down on us as if we are from an inferior category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In his view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families hadn't failed in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
And now we wouldn't find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally when she was a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter are bothered by this.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they are not part of either.
We love listening to the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you're not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
And in the United States we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate matters, from what I've learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as makeshift "ambassadors" for Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and press political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yes, right...
That's not going to happen.
There is too much grudge.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us aren't so sure it's a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, folks.
It's fair.
If some Mexicans are still not prepared to forgive the United States for the way it treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated far less time ago.
Hmmm.
Perhaps we are more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
Ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could well be an unlikely basis for peace
Can there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the usual futile discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel's metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their long-standing conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything in tatters whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional uproar.
Perhaps this will make their struggle even bloodier than before.
However, there are reasons to think that its deadly stalemate could run aground.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism currently seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 holds, this week's clashes have bolstered hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has taken a heavy beating.
And despite killing some of its leaders and straining Gaza's 1.7 million people in one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has been unable to finish off Hamas.
Indeed, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its implacable rivals Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders might conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamists have gained influence throughout the Arab world, Hamas has made rich and powerful friendships.
Turkey, a resurgent regional power that had previously been Israel's closest Muslim ally, has embraced Hamas' cause. So has Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic states in the Gulf.
Jubilant Hamas members say the Islamist crescent is encircling Israel, from Lebanon in the north, where the Hezbollah party-militia dominates, to Syria, where increasingly Islamist rebels could topple Bashar Assad, to Jordan, where Hamas allies are threatening the king.
Particularly on Israel's southern flank, the growth of the Muslim Brotherhood led by President Muhammad Morsi in Egypt, by far the most populous and pivotal of the Arab countries, has changed the balance of the region.
Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, did not have much time for Hamas.
In contrast, the Muslim Brotherhood is Hamas' first cousin and its leaders are more dependent on popular opinion.
In future diplomatic actions, it is possible that Hamas will emerge as a protagonist that cannot be excluded, not even Israel and the United States.
Meanwhile, Israel's hardliners will draw the opposite conclusion.
As far as the military question is concerned, they have put Hamas in its place.
Israel's Iron Dome anti-missile system has proven its effectiveness and many of Hamas' missiles have been destroyed.
Israelis will sleep more peacefully... for some time.
On diplomacy, the United States is more assertive than ever; Many European countries also blamed Hamas for initiating the latest wave of violence.
First and foremost, Israel has prospered. Especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets fired from Gaza have killed some 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has not had too many suicide bombers, thanks in part to the barrier that corrodes the West Bank, the main piece of territory aspiring to become a state of Palestine, and protects Jewish settlements that continue to swell even though,  According to international law, they are illegal.
Mr Netanyahu, whose Likud party has joined an even more hardline group led by Avigdor Lieberman in the run-up to elections on January 22, is in a good position.
Why pamper those twisted Palestinians by giving them a state of their own?
If they really ruled in the West Bank, wouldn't they fire rockets as their compatriots have done in Gaza?
It's better to have them behind that wall and give them a good blow if they raise their heads.
Perhaps the hard wing will prevail, although the Arab Spring could alter its calculus.
Even if Islamists who take power in Egypt and elsewhere may not have much appreciation for Israel, their priority will be to address internal difficulties.
Israel's defense budget is larger than that of its four Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with the area's superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments improve their economies.
That the pragmatic Mr. Morsi worked with Barack Obama to achieve the ceasefire bodes well and could mark the beginning of something.
Israelis, too, should think long-term.
With the rest of the Arab world becoming more democratic, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that will one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, just as a bus exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The crackdown is already undermining democracy in the Jewish state and demographics worsen the situation as the Arab population increases.
The bloody missions to Gaza every two or three years to repel Hamas will pay an ever-increasing diplomatic toll.
Both sides need a push from outsiders.
The solution remains the one touted by sensible people on both sides, most of the outside world and this newspaper: two states and the cession of territory by Israel for security reasons.
The hope, small in the short term, is that the ceasefire will give a little more impetus to outsiders who are fighting for this cause.
Egypt, which must begin to curb the flow of weapons into Gaza, along with Turkey and Qatar, is in an unprecedented position to convince Hamas to accept the idea of a Jewish state based on the 1967 borders, with land swaps and a shared Jerusalem.
Arabs outside the issue should also pressure Hamas and Fatah to join.
That would contribute more to the creation of a Palestinian state than the imminent attempt to obtain virtual statehood at the UN.
Mr. Obama also has an important role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term he failed to present his own plan for peace.
Back in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to devote his attention to it.
This attitude is a deplorable vision of the future.
A stable Middle East is in the vital interest of the United States.
This implies a peace agreement between Israel and Palestine.
Tobacco plain packaging law comes into force in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and body parts with diseases are displayed on dull green packs, which are the same for all brands of tobacco
Australia's world-first tobacco and plain packaging law comes into force and replaces brand logos and colours with a dull olive green wrapper, gruesome images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and babies sick as children of smoking parents.
Except for the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the packs, mandatory since Saturday, are the brand names, all of them printed in a small font.
It is the strictest regime in the world applied to tobacco packaging.
