Petronella Wyatt: "I was bullied out of Oxford for being a Tory"
University students are not attacked for their views only now
I can't remember a time in my life when I haven't been dreaming of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and older brother had been to what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary Greek symposium that promoted the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 80s to study history, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and burst into tears.
My friends were puzzled.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had dropped out because I did not tolerate some university classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I was leaving because I was forced to drink from chipped cups.
The truth was less funny.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my quirky name, nor the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for one reason only, which in the cradle of the so-called enlightenment was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a leading adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative Party.
You may wonder what that is coming to now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalised and growing hatred of Conservative Party students is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them called for the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's JCR say they are "often seriously ostracized, personally attacked and treated as persona non grata" for their political views.
They want to create a seat on their college's equal opportunity committee to make sure they can express their opinions freely.
Their plight was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics and which portrayed the Tories as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
It showed postgraduate student Joe Cooke, former chairman of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, sporting a silver suit and a cane with a silver hilt.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as "scapegoats" for the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice-chairman of the Conservative Party Association at the University of Nottingham, told a Sunday newspaper that "there is a growing left-wing trend in universities.
People assume we're like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other."
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student in Corpus Christi who introduced the motion for greater protection, says this environment is "uncomfortable," while Stephanie Cherill, 19, president-elect of the OUCA, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
"This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members," he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one o'clock.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was at an all-time high.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an "honoris causa" degree following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with horror.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming the new university students, when the new students get to know each other and get to know the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I discovered that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative university students, but participated in it willingly.
The policy of the miners' strike, privatization and the government's opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached the wooden rooms of the seminary.
The first one I attended had to translate eighteenth-century French texts into English and I wasn't prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
I didn't give a single one.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like sponge cake dough, knew well how to expel bad bile.
"Are the Thatcherites refusing to learn French or are they just dumb?" he asked.
The other college students laughed.
My eyes burned with the tears I was trying to hold back.
"I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you're not too busy meeting people," Pitt growled.
I returned to my room like a soul in sorrow.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college. Then I felt a light pat on the back.
He was a sophomore English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
"I know who you are," he said kindly.
"I'm afraid that's how things go.
They mess with anyone who is suspected of being a Tory.
For me it is very complicated, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it will be even worse.
Many newcomer Tories appear to be Labour."
Later, in a local pub, I cowardly tried to disguise.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick proved futile.
A first-year student of Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contaminated."
Other students adopted that little song.
I became the dirty pervert.
"How do Tories have sex?" one asked.
"They beat up each other, don't they?"
I felt the same way homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the '60s.
Could I one day lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to meet like-minded people only after dark?
Should I become Labour and suppress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me presented themselves as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History at my college.
They hated him for being not only from the Conservative party, but also Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
I was barely around.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You're not going to be happy here," he told me.
I began commuting daily from Oxford to my parents' home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
He didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 40s, all political points of view were accepted.
"But it's the best place in the world," he said sadly.
"They would never do that, not there among my dear dreaming needles.
Even my communist friends always had an impeccable attitude."
Her sore eyes began to blur.
"Give him another chance.
I'm sure they've done it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you left him."
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to the pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar where another history professor had insinuated, quite seriously, that I was an "enemy of the people," I decided to do the same.
Red with embarrassment inside, I admitted that my parents had "brainwashed" me and called them "stupid old men."
The truce was short-lived.
It was my father who put the final nail in the coffin of my university career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch's press.
My door was locked.
I was inside curled up in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Perhaps you will call me weak weepers.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which has not only trained 14 Conservative party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
