Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: AIDS positive.
"It was as if a bomb fell on me," he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make "softer", without obvious success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to inform himself about it; With such determination that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 90s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him "because he had a cut."
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive this syndrome and do it with quality of life.
However, ignorant of their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already wreaked havoc, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, at least of the first reported cases, "the great achievement means at this time that the survival of a patient who starts treatment in a timely manner and the survival of the general population, is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV Unit of the HCG.  Jaime Andrade Villanueva, after referring that this information was endorsed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and expert in HIV / AIDS, Andrade Villanueva commented that since 2008, scientists had concluded that AIDS was not a fatal sentence, but the years of survival and quality of life depend on the degree of involvement to the immune system that patients present at the beginning of the diagnosis, with better expectations for those who are not drug users:  up to 30 years with a CD4 count and 50 years, when they report 500 CD4.
In simple words, this means that whoever receives the diagnosis of HIV positive at 25 years of age, under these terms "as long as he remains in control he will be able to live without problems until he is 75 years old," explained the interviewee.
To measure this progress, it should be remembered that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years on average.
Although mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS fell from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths until May of this year; However, universal access to antiretroviral drugs has been ensured since 2005.
- Why are there still deaths?
- It seems to me that the problem is not one of access to treatment.
That's how I visualize it, that's how it has happened to us in our hospital.
At least in the last 12 years we have not had a shortage of medicine, the problem is that patients arrive very advanced because they do not know their state of infection, that is, in late stages of the disease.
He gave a blunt fact: "Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what has to be done to have a greater impact on global mortality, is to make earlier diagnoses and, therefore, detection tests have to be offered massively, to all people who require it. "
In his proposal specialists and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) coincide, also the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to be tested at a private laboratory, only motivated because a friend had done it and, despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma.  A cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better blow myself three times a week," they say not in my case.
The change was for the better, I eat well, I exercise, I take medications.
To date, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
I live a normal life, just like anyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I take care of myself and the other person," said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to motivate with his testimony those who today, in the framework of World AIDS Day, are afraid.
That they get tested, if they were at risk, that the sooner they know if they are HIV positive, the better and if they already have the diagnosis, that they learn that they can live like any person, being responsible.
That, his message, sums up the battle slogan against AIDS in 2012.
