There are large gaps between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has taken up the HIV cause.
And the biggest is in prevention.
In the places dedicated to this task "the distribution of condoms has actually increased, before they gave us one or two, now they give us packages of a hundred, and that is very good but it turns out that there are those who today, still, do not have access to a condom," he said.
Among those most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
"What do you want them for?" is a common question, with derision and value judgments of social workers, school counselors, pharmacy employees and health personnel, to which adolescents do not want to be exposed, said the communicator.
He proposed reorienting this ineffective distribution; That condoms are not only behind the counters and those hundred are in public toilet dispatchers in the places that young people frequent.
It is not motivating promiscuity.
Nor is it about paying them for the chelas and the motel, as Governor Emilio González responded, when asked if there would be distribution of condoms in his Administration.
"That's not how sexuality is, it's best to bring condoms closer to those who already practice sexual activity," he said.
Keys In Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 of AIDS and 1,317 of HIV).
The state ranks 4th nationally in new and cumulative cases of AIDS and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections correspond to the sexual route, 6% to the blood route and 2% to the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50 thousand people may be living with HIV since for a registered case there are 4 to 5 people who do not know it.
