Héctor "Hetin" Reyes: "Basketball has been my life"
Globetrotters of basketball Héctor "Hetin" Reyes was linked to the sport of the plank for more than 60 years and, thanks to him, he traveled the whole world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have such a broad mental collection of local basketball history as Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
Before a stroke confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a player of minor categories, player of the National Superior Basketball, proxy and leader in the BSN with the Vaqueros de Bayamón or president of the Basketball Federation.
"I wore many hats in basketball throughout my life, including several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the National Team and federation president during the 90s," Reyes recalled during a Primera Hora visit to his home in Bayamón, where he resides with Isabel, his faithful wife of more than 50 years.
"Basketball has been my life."
Reyes is not exaggerating in making that assertion.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia that denote his extensive career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all, the ones he treasures with the most emotion are those that recall his time with the Cowboys from the mid-50s as a player until 1982, when he turned 15 years serving as a co-attorney or proxy of the franchise.
"Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to be part of eight Cowboys championships since 1967, either as a proxy, co-agent or manager.
There were many years of satisfaction, including the five championships run from 1971 to 1975.
And then I said goodbye with one in 1981, Jerome Mincy's BSN debut year.
From then on, "Cuco" Ortiz took over, who was a great administrator," Reyes said.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had coached here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me, "I have you a very strong player, 6"7" tall.
Do you want it?"
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then recommended sniper Raymond Gausse, who was native and was one of our best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had given Bayamon a championship, Gausse would help bring in another one.
The championship of the Cowboys with Gausse enjoyed it, but already at a distance, because by 1988 he was already a federative boss.
For that time he preferred to enjoy his performances and those of Mincy in the National Team.
I remember when we first beat the United States during the Olympic Qualifier in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Cup, where we came fourth and should have been bronze if not for that Canadian referee who made us repeat the final play for the second time, Reyes said.
Is that group from the 1990 World Cup the best National Team you've ever seen?
It is among the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team in the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won gold and gave the U.S. team a fight, which was quite similar to the one that won us bronze in the World Cup.
That team not only repeated Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and "Piculín" (Ortiz), but also had (Javier) "Toñito" Colón and James Carter young, the León brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quixote" Morales, who had not been able to be in the 90 due to a knee injury.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of personnel, but gave us a gold medal and a great joy was the 1995 Olympic Qualifier in Neuquén, Argentina.
With role players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and a youth Rolando Hourruitiner replacing the players suspended by the mess of the Pan American of Mar del Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who has been the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, that has been Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers at the level of international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at that level like Piculín did.
And that's not counting his career in the different leagues he played.
Who has been the best Puerto Rican leader?
That's very difficult.
We have had a very good litter that includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
Of the young people, I really like the work of Leo Arill.
What do you consider your greatest achievement in the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious era of the National Team between 1988 and 1995 and that in the early 90s the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What was left for you to do?
There were things I would have liked to implement, such as the regionalization of minor categories.
For example, that the boys from Ponce only played in their area and only faced teams from other corners of the island in the national playoffs.
Right now children travel and play too much unnecessarily.
At least I see the fruit of the compulsory certifications and course for leaders, table officials and referees.
That pleases me.
What do you do now?
The most I do is listen to music, watch videos of the music of my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course, enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been with me.
Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born on September 21, 1931, in Fort Worth (Texas), became world famous for his central role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R.", in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, malicious and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon J.R. Ewing on the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. for a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon of complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the parent company of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he loved most," the family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original series and sequel, was with Hagman when she died at a Dallas hospital, her publicist, Jeffrey Lane, said.
He brought joy to everyone he met.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, caring and talented, and I will miss him dearly.
"He was an original person and lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and acknowledged that he had been drinking heavily for years.
In 1995 he was found to have a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Years before "Dallas," Hagman became famous on television as a decent guy in the light comedy "I Dream of Jeannie," which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life is altered when he finds an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and takes her to live with him at his house.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was his masterful portrayal of the charmingly obnoxious J.R. that propelled Hagman to his ultimate stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its orbit ran from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional phrase "Who shot J.R.?", designed to generate excitement around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost killed, generated international speculation and millions of risky dollars in bookmakers.
He also helped give the series a ratings record at the time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers tuned in and made "Dallas" the second-most-watched entertainment show in history, behind the 1983 finale of "MASH," which had 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. got her pregnant and then threatened to call her a prostitute unless she left town, but others also had motives to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as an insatiable corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a cheating businessman and a cheating husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), hospitalized.
"I know what I want on J.R.'s tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, on and off screen."
He is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of each of us, who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success for the TNT channel.
It had already finished recording five of the episodes for the second season and a sixth was in process, the network reported.
There was no immediate pronouncement from Warner or TNT on how the series will handle Hagman's loss.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in such classics as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan."
Martin was still a teenager when she had it in 1931 during her marriage to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He tried his luck on the New York stage in the early 1950s, and then served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
While there he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson and married her.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for a long time in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001 he titled his memoir "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life".
"I didn't put anything there that I thought was going to hurt anyone or affect them in any way," he told the Associated Press at the time.
After the liver transplant he became a promoter of organ donation and volunteered at a hospital to assist fearful patients.
"I advise them, I give them courage, I meet with them when they come for their surgeries, and after," he said in 1996.
I try to offer some comfort, like "fear not, it will be a little awkward for a short time, but you're going to be okay."
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in several campaigns.
Course that explores the "End of the World" begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to teach a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible hook: The end of the "long countdown" of the Mayan Calendar, on December 21, to which many people have clung as proof that the end of the world is coming.
But Charmé had no idea what awaited him in the next couple of months: cataclysmic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal cliff that some have called "debtrmagedon," and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where end-time Christian theorists believe the apocalypse will begin.
"I didn't realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever," Charmé told students at Rutgers-Camden University this week.
If you look at what's been happening in the world today as if we're 30 days away and counting, this has been a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those of apocalyptic mentality.
And he's not the only professor offering courses on the "end of the world" this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker is teaching the course "Media, Culture and the End of the World."
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
"We looked at why these ideas proliferate over time," he said, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that guide certain human behavior.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
This month students analyzed films with apocalyptic themes and explored how they compare to real-life examples.
"I've tried to inform students about what's possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
On Penn State's main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course, titled only "The End of the World."
"We didn't add '2012' to always have the option to teach the course again, in case the world doesn't end," Restall said.
Despite the "impending ruin", students must study, generate projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on the eve of Revelation, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night the world is supposed to end," Restall said.
The courses proved quite popular.
"It was saturated in two hours," Restall said of his course for high-grade students, which was filled with 35 students.
We received emails for weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, from people asking if there was still room.
The students, on the other hand, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves," said Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology major from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden.
And it is that the apocalyptic mentality, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing major, said he had seen all the apocalyptic movies.
"I've never heard of a class that could teach that," he said.
I enjoy it.
But no student interviewed — let alone a teacher — said they believed the Dec. 21 expiration date.
"Our first project was about Mayan prophecy and we kind of debunked it," said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old Temple senior from West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it's just a key item on the calendar, Restall said.
But he said there is apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture, going back centuries, in which people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused a boom in these speculations.
"Elsewhere people don't think about this," he said.
Mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a La Salle University religion professor who teaches courses in the Philippines this year, quickly responded to the question of whether he knew of any courses on the "end of the world" there.
"The Philippines does not participate in the end of the world," he wrote, hinting at an exception from a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that over the years there has been talk of many doomsday days, saying that if nothing happens on Dec. 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing that Dec. 21 is the beginning of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are taking the date lightly.
Several said they plan to go to parties "at the end of the world."
"Maybe I'll call some friends to have a laugh together," said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
